### Quick Facts

- Location: Wilmore, Kentucky (20 minutes from Lexington)

- Affiliation: Christian

- Athletics: NAIA Division II, NCCAA Division I, KIAC
- Mascot: Eagles
- Colors: Purple and White

### Overview

Asbury University is a private Christian liberal arts university located in Wilmore, Kentucky. The University offers more than 50 undergraduate majors, graduate degrees in education, media communication and social work, and several certification programs. Asbury is accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges (SACSCOC) and has been named a top-tier National Liberal Arts College by U.S. News & World Report for 10 consecutive years. Asbury is also ranked in the top 10 of the U.S. News list of Best Value Regional Universities (South) and has been named to the President’s Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll every year since the list’s inception in 2006.

### Mission

Asbury University is a community committed to academic excellence and spiritual vitality, preparing men and women for a lifetime of learning, leadership and service to the professions, society, the family and the Church, thereby preparing them to engage their cultures and advance the cause of Christ around the world.

### History

Asbury University was founded in 1890 by Methodist preacher John Wesley Hughes as a “school of prophecy” for the training of preachers and missionaries. The school was named after Francis Asbury, the first American bishop of the Methodist Episcopal Church. The school was originally located in downtown Wilmore, but moved to its current location in 1910. The school became a four-year college in 1928 and was renamed Asbury College. In 2010, the school changed its name to Asbury University to reflect its growing graduate programs.

### Academics

Asbury University offers more than 50 undergraduate majors, graduate degrees in education, media communication and social work, and several certification programs. The University is accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges (SACSCOC) and has been named a top-tier National Liberal Arts College by U.S. News & World Report for 10 consecutive years. Asbury is also ranked in the top 10 of the U.S. News list of Best Value Regional Universities (South) and has been named to the President’s Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll every year since the list’s inception in 2006.

### Student Life

Asbury University has a vibrant student life with more than 50 student organizations, including academic, service, and special interest groups. The University also has a strong intramural sports program and a variety of student-led ministries. The University is home to the Asbury Eagles, who compete in the NAIA Division II, NCCAA Division I, and KIAC conferences.

### Campus

Asbury University’s campus is located in Wilmore, Kentucky, a small town 20 minutes from Lexington. The campus is situated on 200 acres of rolling hills and features a variety of academic, residential, and recreational facilities. The University also has a satellite campus in Orlando, Florida, which offers graduate programs in education and media communication.

### Notable Alumni

Asbury University has a long list of notable alumni, including:

- Billy Graham, evangelist
- J. Edwin Orr, historian and theologian
- John Wesley White, evangelist
- David Jeremiah, pastor and author
- Tony Campolo, sociologist and author
- John Piper, pastor and author
- Ravi Zacharias, apologist and author
- Charles Colson, author and founder of Prison Fellowship
- Jim Wallis, author and founder of Sojourners
- Richard Foster, author and founder of Renovaré

### Conclusion

Asbury University is a private Christian liberal arts university located in Wilmore, Kentucky. The University offers more than 50 undergraduate majors, graduate degrees in education, media communication and social work, and several certification programs. Asbury is accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges (SACSCOC) and has been named a top-tier National Liberal Arts College by U.S. News & World Report for 10 consecutive years. The University has a vibrant student life with more than 50 student organizations and a strong intramural sports program. Asbury is also home to a long list of notable alumni, including Billy Graham, J. Edwin Orr, and David Jeremiah.
